Ultratech (Rewritten)

Target IP: 10.10.248.31
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.248.31 -p- returns the result shown above. There are three TCP ports open on the target machine: FTP and SSH on their standard ports, and some other application on port 31331. Time to perform an aggressive scan against these ports to identify its applications.


Running an aggressive scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.248.31 -p 21,22,31331 returns the result shown above. The higher port seems to be hosting a web application with the name UltraTech as the title. The scan above also detected the target machine is running some sort of Linux. The FTP application on port 21 does not allow anonymous login either. I will begin enumeration with the web application on the higher port.


I performed a web server scan using the command nikto -h http://10.10.248.31:31331/ -Tuning b and obtained the result shown above. One of the interesting information is the robots.txt. Apparently this file contains one entry which is worth checking.

Allow: *
User-Agent: *
Sitemap: /utech_sitemap.txt
Allow: *
User-Agent: *
Sitemap: /utech_sitemap.txt

I browsed to http://10.10.248.31:31331/robots.txt and the entries above was returned to me. I notice the sitemap is /utech_sitemap.txt. I can obtain the sitemap directories if I browse to this location.


And bingo. I obtained the three crucial sitemap locations by browsing to http://10.10.248.31:31331/utech_sitemap.txt as shown above for the web application. Now I can perform further enumeration against these locations.

Enumeration

Port 31331: HTTP

The webpage above is returned to me after visiting the web application on this port. I viewed the source-code of this web application, but I did not find anything useful. Previously, I found another location called /partners.html by looking at the sitemap. This is the only page I have not visited.


I browsed to http://10.10.248.31:31331/partners.html and the login webpage above was returned to me. Since I do not have any credentials, I tried the default credentials such as admin:admin, but I had no luck. I wonder how this application works. I viewed the source-code of this login procedure and found interesting stuff.


The JavaScript source-code of the web application is shown above. To obtain this, I browsed to the http://10.10.248.31:31331/js/api.js. Right away, I notice three unusual things:

  1. The API calls are being made on port 8081 of the target machine according to the getAPIURL() function
  2. There is another API endpoint with the name /ping that takes in the parameter name ip and performs connectivity check according to the checkAPIStatus function
  3. Another API endpoint exists with the name /auth that is responsible for checking the authentication passed by the /partners.html page

Out of all three, the second seems the most interesting to me as I could possibly perform command injection. Time to put this application to test.


I browsed to http://10.10.248.31:8081/ping and passed the value 127.0.0.1 as the parameter by including the parameter name ip, and obtained the result shown above. This applications worked successfully as it performed a ping check. Time to check if it is vulnerable to command injection. I can test this using Burpsuite.

Exploitation

Owning the /ping API Endpoint via Command Injection

When checking the API endpoint for command injection, I found a working payload %0a a.k.a the linefeed option. This is the only payload I found working. I tried using &, |, ;, and others, but I did not have any luck. By using the payload, I was able to inject the commands whoami and id as shown above.


Using the same payload, I injected the command ls and obtained the crucial information shown above. I was able to retrieve the directory listing and found an interesting file with the name utech.db.sqlite. This database seems to be for the /partners.html. Can I obtain the credentials to login to the web application?

Obtaining & Cracking the Credentials from utech.db.sqlite

And bingo. Using the same payload again, I was able to inject the command cat utech.db.sqlite and obtain the contents of the database file as shown above. The database entries are stored in username, password hash, and type format. There are two entries: r00t with the password hash f357a0c52799563c7c7b76c1e7543a32, and admin with the password hash 0d0ea5111e3c1def594c1684e3b9be84. Time to crack these hashes.


I pasted the two password hashes at crackstation and obtained the plaintext as shown above. Now I have the passwords for both users. The credentials I now have are r00t:n100906 and admin:mrsheafy. I can test these credentials against the SSH, FTP, and the login webpage.


I logged into the web application using the credentials r00t:n100906 and obtained the interesting information shown above. It mentions the server's configuration are worth looking at. But I can only do that once I have a foothold on the target machine. Time to put the credentials to test by using the SSH.

Foothold: SSH Access as r00t via Credentials

I ran the command ssh r00t@10.10.248.31 and entered the password n100906 and got a hit as shown above. Now I have access to the target machine as the user r00t via SSH. Time to elevate my privileges now. It is worth looking at the server configuration now.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: r00t user to root user via Docker Group Breakout Privilege Escalation


Running the command id shows this user r00t belongs to the group Docker. And there is a docker image called bash that can be used to breakout.


To escape the docker environment and spawn a root shell, I ran the command docker -H unix:///var/run/docker.sock run -v /:/mnt --rm -it bash chroot /mnt bash as shown above. Now I have a root shell on the target machine.


After gaining a root shell, I browsed to the /root home directory and even obtained the SSH key belonging to this user as shown above. I can copy the SSH key from id_rsa to my machine, change its file permission to 200, and login using the SSH key belonging to the user root. Or we can even put our own SSH key. There are no flags to capture in this challenge. GG.
